  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (if v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (v1 \NATless v0 or v1 is equal to v0 or v0 \NATless v1)))
Proof:
  \Phi is a class and (if \Nat is a set then \Phi is a set) and for all v0, (v0 is an element of \Phi iff (v0 is an element of \Nat and v0 is an object and (n \NATless v0 or n is equal to v0 or v0 \NATless n)))
  \NATzero is an element of \Phi
  for all v0, (if v0 is an element of \Phi then v0 \NATplus \NATone is an element of \Phi)
  Proof:
    m' is an element of \Phi
    if n \NATless m' then the thesis holds
    if n is equal to m' then the thesis holds
    if m' \NATless n then the thesis holds
    Proof:
      k is a natural number and k is positive and n is equal to m' \NATplus k
      if k is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
      if it is wrong that k is equal to \NATone then the thesis holds
      Proof:
