Theorem (preservation_of_ordering_under_right_addition):
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (v2 \NATless v1 iff v2 \NATplus v0 \NATless v1 \NATplus v0))))
Proof:
  if n \NATless m then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    l is a natural number and l is positive and m is equal to n \NATplus l
    m \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus k and n \NATplus l \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l
    n \NATplus k \NATless m \NATplus k
  Qed.
  if n \NATplus k \NATless m \NATplus k then the thesis holds
  Proof:
    l is a natural number and l is positive and m \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l
    n \NATplus k \NATplus l is equal to n \NATplus k \NATplus l and n \NATplus k \NATplus l is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus k and n \NATplus l \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus k
    m \NATplus k is equal to n \NATplus l \NATplus k
    m is equal to n \NATplus l
    n \NATless m
  Qed.
Qed.

Theorem:
  for all v0, (for all v1, (for all v2, (if v2 is a natural number and v1 is a natural number and v0 is a natural number then (v2 \NATless v1 iff v0 \NATplus v2 \NATless v0 \NATplus v1))))
Proof:
  k \NATplus n is equal to n \NATplus k and k \NATplus m is equal to m \NATplus k
  k \NATplus n \NATless k \NATplus m iff n \NATplus k \NATless m \NATplus k
